{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}
'''BTN Television''', an acronym for '''Bornfree Technologies Network''', is a television broadcaster on Arua Hill where they moved in 2015, after starting from Anyafio, a suburb of [[Arua]]. It is registered by [[Uganda Communications Commission]]<ref>[http://id.famedpages.com/www/btn+arua Famed Pages]</ref> to broadcast on UHF 23 in West Nile and UHF 61 in Kampala. It was the first television station from Arua and [[West Nile sub-region|West Nile]]. It started broadcasts from the northern end of the outer crescent road off Oda Road.
[[File:BTN TV Arua.jpg|thumb|BTN TV and Nile FM studios in Anyafio Village, Arua Hill Division during the 2000s]]

==History==
BTN started test broadcasts in 2003, but celebrated 10 years of existence in 2014 alongside its sister radio station - 94.1 Nile FM<ref>[http://allafrica.com/stories/200410261113.html Arua Has 7 Radio Stations (The Monitor, 26 October 2004)]</ref> that was launched in 2004. It is famous for premiering music videos by West Nile artistes who do not get enough airplay on other Ugandan TV stations. English and [[Lugbara language|Lugbara]] are the most common languages heard on the station.

==Programming==
BTN TV is a house of music, movies, cartoons, documentaries, local shows and international news courtesy of mainly [[BBC Television]]. BTN focusses on TV programs that promote culture, democracy, peace, tolerance, reconciliation, health, agriculture and entrepreneurship. In 2014, locally produced shows included the news bulletins, Early Riser by Mara (Nsangi) - the Sweet Girl, BTN Sports with Aloro (Saidi) plus TOK, Lunch Beat Request by (Amina) Likia (around lunchtime) and Sunset Chat with Rashid and Lillian.

